  "response_text": "Building muscle requires a combination of strength training, proper nutrition, and adequate recovery. Here’s a comprehensive fitness plan designed to help you build muscle effectively.\n\n### Fitness Plan Overview\n\n**Duration:** 12 weeks  \n**Frequency:** 4-5 days per week  \n**Goal:** Muscle hypertrophy (growth)  \n**Equipment Needed:** Dumbbells, barbells, resistance bands, bench, pull-up bar, and access to a gym if possible.\n\n### Weekly Workout Schedule\n\n#### Day 1: Upper Body (Push)\n- Bench Press: 4 sets of 6-8 reps\n- Incline Dumbbell Press: 3 sets of 8-10 reps\n- Overhead Press: 4 sets of 6-8 reps\n- Tricep Dips: 3 sets of 8-10 reps\n- Lateral Raises: 3 sets of 12-15 reps\n- Plank: 3 sets of 30-60 seconds\n\n#### Day 2: Lower Body\n- Squats: 4 sets of 6-8 reps\n- Deadlifts: 4 sets of 6-8 reps\n- Lunges (Walking or Stationary): 3 sets of 10 reps per leg\n- Leg Curls: 3 sets of 10-12 reps\n- Calf Raises: 4 sets of 12-15 reps\n- Core Exercise (e.g., Russian Twists): 3 sets of 15-20 reps per side\n\n#### Day 3: Rest or Active Recovery\n- Light cardio (walking, cycling, swimming) for 20-30 minutes\n- Stretching or yoga\n\n#### Day 4: Upper Body (Pull)\n- Pull-Ups or Lat Pull-Downs: 4 sets of 6-8 reps\n- Bent Over Rows: 4 sets of 6-8 reps\n- Seated Rows: 3 sets of 8-10 reps\n- Face Pulls: 3 sets of 12-15 reps\n- Bicep Curls: 3 sets of 10-12 reps\n- Ab Wheel Rollouts: 3 sets of 8-10 reps\n\n#### Day 5: Legs & Core\n- Leg Press: 4 sets of 8-10 reps\n- Step-Ups: 3 sets of 10 reps per leg\n- Romanian Deadlifts: 4 sets of 8-10 reps\n- Glute Bridges: 3 sets of 10-12 reps\n- Core Circuit (Planks, Side Planks, Bicycle Crunches): 3 rounds of 30-60 seconds each\n\n#### Day 6: Optional Cardio/Conditioning\n- High-Intensity Interval Training (HIIT) for 20-30 minutes\n- Steady-state cardio for 30-45 minutes (running, cycling, etc.)\n\n#### Day 7: Rest & Recovery\n- Focus on hydration, nutrition, and sleep.\n\n### Nutrition Plan\n\n1. **Protein Intake:** Aim for 1.2 to 2.2 grams of protein per kilogram of body weight. Include sources like lean meats, fish, eggs, dairy, legumes, and plant-based proteins.\n\n2. **Carbohydrates:** Include complex carbohydrates such as whole grains, fruits, and vegetables to fuel workouts.\n\n3. **Healthy Fats:** Incorporate sources like avocados, nuts, seeds, and olive oil for overall health and hormone production.\n\n4. **Hydration:** Drink plenty of water throughout the day, especially before, during, and after workouts.\n\n5. **Meal Timing:** Consider eating a balanced meal or snack containing protein and carbohydrates before and after workouts to optimize muscle recovery.\n\n### Recovery and Rest\n\n- **Sleep:** Aim for 7-9 hours of quality sleep each night.\n- **Active Recovery:** Incorporate light activities like walking, stretching, or yoga on rest days.\n- **Listen to Your Body:** If you're feeling fatigued or sore, don’t hesitate to take an extra rest day as needed.\n\n### Progress Tracking\n\n- **Weight and Measurements:** Track your body weight and muscle measurements (arms, chest, waist, legs) every 2-4 weeks.\n- **Strength Progress:** Keep a log of your weights and reps for each exercise to monitor your progress.\n- **Adjustments:** If you’re not gaining strength or muscle, consider adjusting caloric intake or exercise intensity.\n\n### Important Notes\n\n- Always warm up before workouts (5-10 minutes of light cardio and dynamic stretching).\n- Consider consulting a fitness professional or personal trainer if you're unfamiliar with any exercises or need personalized guidance.\n- Consult a healthcare provider before starting any new exercise or nutrition program, especially if you have pre-existing conditions.\n\nBy following this plan consistently and focusing on your nutrition, you should be able to build muscle effectively over the next 12 weeks. Good luck!",
